docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 nginx
------------------------------------------
Here:

'''8080 = Host port (your PC)-Host Port
Exists on your computer (Windows/Linux/macOS).
You use it in your browser.
Must be unique.

-------------------------------------------------
80 = Container port (inside Docker) -Exists inside the Docker container.
The application listens on this port.
Multiple containers can use the same container port.
-----------------------------------------------------
Q: What does -p 8080:80 mean?

Answer:

8080 is the host port.
80 is the container port.
Requests to http://localhost:8080 are forwarded to port 80 inside the container.
One-line shortcut to remember

Left side = Host (outside Docker), Right side = Container (inside Docker). '''
---------------------

Your Browser
      │
http://localhost:8080
      │
      ▼
Windows Port 8080
      │
      ▼
Docker Engine
      │
      ▼
Container Port 80
      │
      ▼
Nginx Web Server


http://localhost:8080

the request goes to:

Windows (or WSL)
Docker Engine
Docker forwards it to port 80 inside the container.
Nginx receives the request and sends back the web page.



